{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1778729061,"nonce":"ngjYsejpl8SnDijYt2lSPLdf/VA=","message":"cs2019's human experiments use a narrow disturbance class (curl force fields applied on ~20% of randomly interleaved trials — Fig 2, p. 8139). But cs2019's **model** is full-state H∞ (B_w = I_n after the Eq 9→10 lumping — see companion comment on this issue for the math). The model's predictions are derived from a worst-case over a *much broader* perturbation class than the experiment literally provides. The behavioural fit therefore implies:\n\n**Humans whose strategy fits this model are defending against a broader perturbation class than the experiment imposes.** They're not Bayes-updating on the specific curl-field generator they've been exposed to; they're adopting a robust-strategy policy consistent with \"I don't know the disturbance model, so I default to worst-case over a broad admissible class.\"\n\ncs2019 endorses this framing explicitly: *\"this design is advantageous where there is no model of the disturbance available\"* + *\"the robust controller's predictions about the system are insensitive to model errors\"* + *\"this uncertainty was random from trial to trial, but it was not random within a trial\"* (p. 8137-8138). The H∞ framework is the math for a controller that adopts the worst-case stance over a model-class it cannot pin down.\n\n**Implication for our work:** when inducing the cs2019 signature in trained RNNs, the right training game isn't the one matched to a specific narrow perturbation distribution — it's the game whose worst-case admits the broadest perturbations the controller plausibly faces. The mathematical machinery for this is `B_w = I_n` in the Riccati / a free time-varying full-state ε adversary in minimax training. `020a65b` is the implementation hook.\n\nThis also clarifies why narrower adversary classes (flavor-B's `ΔA·x`, or gaussian-bump force profiles) are *training methods* in their own right that induce *their own* signatures — they're not \"wrong\" attempts at cs2019, they're different formal training settings that should produce different behavioural signatures. The multi-signature menu in the synthesis body captures this: different adversary class → different game → potentially different signature pair.","files":null}]}